tool.name: SATLayoutPrelim
tool.displayname: Create Single Axis Tracker Preliminary Layout

param.name: buildable_area
param.dialogReference: Feature class polygon that defines the buildable area for the project.

param.name: xyzUnit
param.dialogReference: Identifies the horizontal units of the dimensions for the layout design inputs (Foot or Meter)
param.pythonReference: Horizontal units must match the units of the projection

param.name: moduleType
param.dialogReference: A string designating which module is being used in the design (outputs to the layout summary table)

param.name: modPower
param.dialogReference: Capacity of the module in Watts

param.name: modLength
param.dialogReference: Length of the module in the measurement units

param.name: modWidth
param.dialogReference: Width of the module in the measurement units

param.name: tracker_config
param.expression: Mechanically-linked rows | Unlinked rows | Custom inputs
param.dialogReference: Assigns default spacings for mechanically linked rows and unlinked rows for the bearing gap, motor/gearbox gap, and module gap. Custom inputs can also be chosen, which will open the inputs for bearing gap, motor/gearbox gap, and module gap.

param.name: bearingGap
param.dialogReference: Gap for bearings, if applicable. Default for mechanically-linked rows is 0 and for unlinked rows 0.541 ft.

param.name: gearboxGap
param.dialogReference: Gap for the motor or gearbox. Default for mechanically linked rows is 3 ft and for unlinked rows 6 ft.

param.name: modGap
param.dialogReference: Gap between modules. Default 0.021 ft.

param.name: rowGap
param.dialogReference: North-south gap between rows (non-road)

param.name: inverterType
param.dialogReference: A string designating the inverter used for the layout

param.name: inverterSize
param.dialogReference: The inverter size in megawatts (AC)

param.name: inverterWidth
param.dialogReference: Width of the inverter in the measurement units

param.name: inverterLength
param.dialogReference: Length of the inverter in the measurement units

param.name: dcacRatio
param.dialogReference: The ratio of DC to AC power for the project

param.name: aspectRatio
param.dialogReference: The aspect ratio for the tracker (currently 1 in portrait and 2 in portrait)

param.name: modString
param.dialogReference: Number of modules per string

param.name: stringsRow
param.dialogReference: Number of strings per full row

param.name: GCR
param.dialogReference: The ground cover ratio for the design

param.name: roadWidth
param.dialogReference: The width of the site roads, including shoulders

param.name: stringsRowsOption
param.dialogReference: Designates whether the output layout will merge the strings together for each row or output individual strings

param.name: layoutOutput
param.dialogReference: The output feature class layer for the layout

param.name: inverterOutput
param.dialogReference: The output feature class layer for the inverters

param.name: summaryOutput
param.dialogReference: The output summary table for the layout

tool.summary: • Generates a single axis tracker layout based on input parameters.
tool.usage:
• This tool generates a layout based on a project or buildable area and tracker specifications, including GCR, modules per string, inverter size, DC/AC ratio, aspect ratio, and site road width. Advanced options are available.

  • The output is designed to be in “inverter blocks” based on the calculated number of strings per inverter. Inverters are not placed in this tool. Site roads divide up the inverter blocks.

  • This tool generates a preliminary layout for an initial look at potential capacity for a site and is not intended to be for construction-ready layouts or design.

  • The DC/AC ratio should be considered a target. The number of inverters in the produced layout will vary depending on the shape of the buildable area. Inverters can be added by using the ArcGIS Pro editing tools.

  • Inverter placement by default is the northeast corner of the inverter blocks.

  • When the option for outputting strings is used, the strings generated are of equal dimensions, which is not necessarily correct depending on the tracker configuration. A future update of the tool will modify the strings to include motor/gearbox gaps and size the strings appropriately based on inputs.

Layout design can be edited using editing tools, specifically the “Move to” tool using measured distances (lengths of strings, center-to-center distance).
